          "body": "After seven cycles of seven years — forty-nine years — a fiftieth year is proclaimed. The announcement vehicle is the shophar, the ram's horn, sounded across the whole land on the tenth day of the seventh month: the Day of Atonement (25:9). The timing is not incidental. The Jubilee is announced from within Israel's most solemn liturgical event — the day when the nation's sin is covered and the land purged. The word proclaimed is deror — liberty, release — the same term Isaiah will use of the eschatological liberation in Isaiah 61:1. In the Jubilee year, every Israelite returns to his ancestral property and to his family (25:10). The fiftieth year is holy (25:12); its produce is eaten without the normal agricultural cycle because the year itself belongs to God. The Jubilee is Israel's enacted testimony that economic history is not final. No displacement, no poverty, no bondage accumulated over half a century can survive the Jubilee's arrival. The ram's horn that announces it sounds from the sanctuary, declaring that the God who atones for sin also resets the social order."
