          "title": "The impoverished brother — sustained, not exploited",
          "body": "Leviticus 25:35-38 pivots from land law to personal ethics. The scenario is specific: 'a countryman of yours becomes poor and his means with regard to you falter.' The verb translated 'falter' (mot) carries the sense of tottering, about to fall. God's command is not to wait until the brother has fallen but to sustain him while he is still standing — 'that he may live with you' (25:35). The prohibition on interest (25:36-37) is grounded not in economic theory but in two theological facts: fear of God (25:36) and the memory of Egypt. The argument of verse 38 is stunning: 'I am the LORD your God, who brought you out of the land of Egypt to give you the land of Canaan and to be your God.' The Exodus-memory does not merely prohibit exploitation; it generates positive obligation. Because God sustained Israel as helpless slaves in Egypt and brought them out, Israel must sustain the helpless brother in Canaan. The Exodus creates the ethics of generosity."
