          "body": "Leviticus 25 does not end with itself. The chapter's deror-language (25:10) appears again in Isaiah 61:1-2, where the Servant of YHWH is anointed to 'proclaim liberty to captives' and 'the favorable year of the LORD' — Jubilee language applied to eschatological liberation. When Jesus reads that text in the Nazareth synagogue (Luke 4:18-21) and declares 'today this Scripture has been fulfilled in your hearing,' He is claiming to be the Jubilee's ultimate referent: the One who announces the final deror from sin, debt, and bondage. The kinsman-redeemer (go'el) of Leviticus 25 finds its canonical fulfilment in Christ, who redeems what the family lost — not ancestral property but the humanity distorted by sin. The land-rest of the Sabbatical Year looks forward to the cosmic Sabbath rest of Hebrews 4:9-11. The Jubilee calendar's insistence that no poverty is permanent, no bondage is final, and no displacement is the last word is the temporal form of the gospel's claim that death, exile, and condemnation do not have the final word in a world governed by the God who redeems."
